<HEADLINE>
<P>
3 ROOF BLAZES BLAMED ON HOME FIREPLACES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By TONY MARCANO, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Three Christmas Day fires -- including one started by burning gift boxes and 
wrapping -- caused substantial damage to two homes and minor damage to another, 
Orange County fire officials said. 
</P>
<P>
The blazes, in Placentia, Yorba Linda and Villa Park, all started on the roofs 
of the houses, said Orange County Fire Department Capt. Dan Young. In one of 
the fires, a homeowner was unaware that his roof was on fire until a neighbor 
pounded on his door to warn him. 
</P>
<P>
Young said the homeowner, identified as Richard McMillan, 43, of Potomac 
Avenue, Placentia, was "up with his kids, who were playing with their toys, and 
smelled smoke" shortly after 9 a.m., but was unable to determine the source. 
</P>
<P>
"About 10 minutes later, (a neighbor) came over and pounded on the door, saying 
that the roof was on fire," Young said. 
</P>
<P>
The fire, caused by burning embers from the fireplace, was brought under 
control in 30 minutes and caused $140,000 in damage, he said. 
</P>
<P>
In the Yorba Linda fire, a couple was in their Casa Loma Avenue home when they 
smelled smoke and discovered that their roof was engulfed by flames. They 
called 911 at 11:40 a.m. to report the fire at their converted farmhouse, Young 
said. 
</P>
<P>
Young said investigators determined that cracks in the chimney's mortar allowed 
heat to escape into the attic and set combustible materials ablaze. Fire damage 
was set at $80,000. 
</P>
<P>
In the third blaze, investigators determined that burning wrapping paper was 
the cause of a Villa Park fire on Dorothy Circle. 
</P>
<P>
Young said the homeowner was in his home with eight other people when his 
fireplace "went out of control." 
</P>
<P>
"He was burning some Christmas wrappings and boxes, which we specifically (tell 
residents) 'don't do,' " Young said. "Sections of boxes and paper blew right up 
through the chimney and landed on the roof, which caught fire." 
</P>
<P>
King and his other guests battled the blaze with garden hoses and kept damage 
to a minimum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
